<DOC><DOCNO> AP890224-0061 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0634EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-24 0498</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0517</SECOND><HEAD>Snow Along East Coast; Cold Sweeps Through South</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The Carolinas were digging out from a storm today that dumped upto 7 inches of snow in some areas, and the outlook for much of theEast Coast was for more of the same.   A low pressure area off the North Carolina coast continuedproducing snow from eastern Georgia across the Carolinas and alongthe Atlantic Coast. The storm center was to move northeast andproduce wintry weather in New England late tonight.   Snowfall was heaviest in North Carolina, where 7 inches fell inLincoln County. Charlotte reported 5 inches. Driving conditions werehazardous and numerous accidents were reported due to freezing snowand ice on roads.   Snowfall in South Carolina Thursday night included 5 inches atGreenwood, and 3 to 5 inches in Rock Hill.   Heavy snow also fell in Georgia, but was diminishing as the stormsystem moved north.   The snow was to spread up the Atlantic Coast to much of NewEngland today.   An arctic air mass plunged as far south as Florida this morning,and the 34-degree temperature at Orlando was lower than the 37degrees Minot, N.D., posted.   Wind chill readings in Georgia were in the single digits earlytoday.   The nation's high temperature Thursday was 92 degrees at Santee,Calif.   Today's forecast called for snow in North Carolina, the MiddleAtlantic States and New England; snow squalls in northwest New Yorkand northeast Minnesota; and rain showers in the Pacific Northwest.   Temperatures were to reach the teens and the 20s in inland NewEngland, the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes; and the 30s and 40s incoastal New England, the Middle Atlantic States, Florida, the GulfCoast, the Tennessee Valley, the Mississippi Valley, parts of thePlains, northern Rockies and the Pacific Northwest.   The mercury was to approach 70 degrees over the southern tip ofTexas and climb into the 80s in southern New Mexico, Arizona andparts of California. High temperatures in Florida were to be in thelow 50s, with 60s in the remainder of the nation.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 8degrees below zero at Lansing, Mich., to 67 at Phoenix.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 19 windy; Boston 28 windy; Buffalo 7 partlycloudy; Charleston, S.C. 31 snow; Cincinnati 15 snow; Cleveland 12snow; Detroit 08 fair; Miami 43 windy; New York 26 windy;Philadelphia 28 windy; Pittsburgh 11 snow; Portland, Maine 17 fair;Washington 26 wind.   _Central: Bismarck 31 fair; Chicago 10 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 34fair; Denver 38 fair; Des Moines 13 cloudy; Indianapolis 12 fair;Kansas City 23 cloudy; Nashville 19 fair; New Orleans 30 fair; St.Louis 14 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 45 fair; Anchorage 16 cloudy; Las Vegas 56fair; Los Angeles 60 partly cloudy; Phoenix 65 partly cloudy; SaltLake City 31 foggy; San Diego 61 partly cloudy; San Francisco 48partly cloudy; Seattle 37 fair.   _Canada: Toronto 1 fair.</TEXT></DOC>